               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491029-name-1002" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1002" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1002" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1002" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am salesman to Richard Parry, of Deptford, clothier. On 1st Oct., between five and six o'clock I missed a pair of trowsers from the door-post, which I had seen safe half an hour previous—these are them (<hi rend="italic">pro<lb></lb>duced</hi>)—<hi rend="italic">they</hi> are Richard Parry and Son's property.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184910290173"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18491029-name-1003" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1003" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1003" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18491029-name-1003" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WHITE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, R</hi> 180). On 1st Oct. I was on duty in Dept<lb></lb>ford—I saw the prisoner, with two other boys, loitering about Mr. Parry's shop about three-quarters of an hour—they then went to the shop, and after remaining a short time, left—I turned round, and saw the prisoner putting something under his coat; he was then about five yards from the shop—I pursued him, and just before I overtook him, he dropped this pair of trowsers—he said, "I did not take them"—I took him to the station.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> My father won't keep me; it was not me that stole them.</p>
               <p>
